statement.p:
 Spot and correct the error(s) in the following calculation.


f(x)&=\frac{2x}{x+1}

f'(x)&=\frac{2(x+1)+2x}{(x+1)^2}

&=\frac{2(x+1)}{(x+1)^2}

&=\frac{2}{x+1}

solution.p:
 The correct version is:


f(x)&=\frac{2x}{x+1}

f'(x)&=\frac{2(x+1)\textcolor{red}{-}2x}{(x+1)^2}

&=\frac{2}{(x+1)^2}

  We can rewrite slightly to make every term into a power of t:


s(t)&=3t^4+5t^3-t^{-1}

s'(t)&=4\cdot 3t^{3}+3\cdot 5t^2-(-1)\cdot t^{-2}

&=12t^3+15t^2+\frac{1}{t^2}

Using the quotient rule:


T(x) &= \dfrac{\sqrt{x}+1}{x^2+3}

T'(x)&=\frac{(x^2+3)\left(\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}}\right)-(\sqrt{x}+1)(2x)}{(x^2+3)^2}

answer.p:
The derivative of the function is


 \frac{(1-x^2)\cdot\frac{1}{2\sqrt{x}} - \sqrt{x} \cdot (-2x)}{(1-x^2)^2}
  &= \frac{(1-x^2) - 2x \cdot (-2x)}{2\sqrt{x}(1-x^2)^2}


The derivative is undefined if either x \lt 0 or x = 0,\pm 1 (since the square-root is
undefined for x \lt 0 and the denominator is zero when x=0,1,-1. Putting this together
 the derivative exists for x \gt 0, x\neq 1.

