Using the product rule seems faster than expanding.
f'(x)&=\diff{}{x}\left\{3\sqrt[5]{x}+15\sqrt[3]{x}+8\right\}\left(3x^2+8x-5\right)+ \left(3\sqrt[5]{x}+15\sqrt[3]{x}+8\right)
\amp\hskip2in\diff{}{x}\left\{3x^2+8x-5\right\}
&=\diff{}{x}\left\{3{x}^{\frac{1}{5}}+15{x}^{\frac{1}{3}}+8\right\}\left(3x^2+8x-5\right)+ \left(3\sqrt[5]{x}+15\sqrt[3]{x}+8\right)
\amp\hskip2in\diff{}{x}\left\{3x^2+8x-5\right\}
&=\left(\frac{3}{5}{x}^{\frac{-4}{5}}\!+\!5{x}^{\frac{-2}{3}}\right) \left(3x^2\!+\!8x\!-\!5\right)+ \left(3\sqrt[5]{x}\!+\!15\sqrt[3]{x}+8\right)\left(6x\!+\!8\right)

The question asks us to find where f'(x)=0 and f(x) exists. We can use the formula for the derivative of a reciprocal, Corollary:


f'(x) &= \frac{-\diff{}{x}\left\{\frac{1}{5}x^5+x^4-\frac{5}{3}x^3\right\}}{\left(\frac{1}{5}x^5+x^4-\frac{5}{3}x^3\right)^2}

&=\frac{-\left(x^4+4x^3-{5}x^2\right)}{\left(\frac{1}{5}x^5+x^4-\frac{5}{3}x^3\right)^2}

&=\frac{-x^2\left(x^2+4x-{5}\right)}{\left(\frac{1}{5}x^5+x^4-\frac{5}{3}x^3\right)^2}

&=\frac{-x^2(x+5)(x-1)}{\left(\frac{1}{5}x^5+x^4-\frac{5}{3}x^3\right)^2}


So our candidates for x-values where f'(x)=0 are x=0, x=-5, and x=1. However, we need to check that f exists at these places:  f(0) is undefined (and  f'(0) doesn't exist). So f'(x)=0 only when x=-5 and x=1.

Denote by m the slope of the common tangent, by (x_1,y_1) the point of tangency with y=x^2, and by (x_2,y_2) the point of tangency with y=x^2-2x+2. Then we must have
y_1=x_1^2\qquad y_2=x_2^2-2x_2+2\qquad m=2x_1=2x_2-2=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}
From the m equations we get x_1=\frac{m}{2}, x_2=\frac{m}{2}+1 and
m&=\frac{y_2-y_1}{x_2-x_1}
&=y_2-y_1
&=x_2^2-2x_2+2-x_1^2 & =(x_2-x_1)(x_2+x_1)-2(x_2-1)
&=\left(\frac{m}{2}+1-\frac{m}{2}\right)\left(\frac{m}{2}+1+\frac{m}{2}\right) -2\left(\frac{m}{2}+1-1\right) &=(1)(m+1)-2\frac{m}{2}
&=1
So m=1 and
x_1=\half,\qquad y_1=\frac{1}{4},\qquad x_2=\frac{3}{2},\qquad y_2=\frac{9}{4}-3+2=\frac{5}{4}
An equation of the common tangent is y=x-\frac{1}{4}.

This limit represents the derivative computed at x=2 of the function f(x)=x^{2015}.
To see this, simply use the definition of the derivative at a=2 with f(x)=x^{2015}:


\left.\diff{}{x}\{f(x)\}\right|_{a} &= \lim_{x \to a}\frac{f(x)-f(a)}{x-a}

\left.\diff{}{x}\{x^{2015}\}\right|_{2} &=\lim_{x\to2} \frac{x^{2015}-2^{2015}}{x-2}


Since the derivative of f(x) is 2015\cdot x^{2014}, then its value at x=2 is exactly 2015\cdot 2^{2014}.
